ARCUIA Sensor Fusion
Ryan Breen

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 HARDWARE — SENSOR WIRING (Teensy 4.x)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

IMU (e.g. ICM-42688, BMI088, MPU-6500)
  SDA / SCL → Teensy I2C pins (18 / 19)
  Or SPI: CS, MOSI, MISO, SCK → Teensy SPI0 (10-13)
  Outputs: accel [m/s²], gyro [rad/s]  @ 500 Hz

Magnetometer (e.g. LIS3MDL, QMC5883L)
  SDA / SCL → same I2C bus as IMU (or second bus)
  Output: mag [µT]  @ up to 500 Hz (can repeat last reading)

GPS / GNSS (e.g. u-blox M8N, M9N)
  TX → Teensy Serial1 RX (pin 0)
  Configure module for UBX-NAV-PVT at 10 Hz, 115200 baud
  Parse: latitude [deg], longitude [deg], altitude [m],
         velocity NED [m/s]

Barometer (e.g. BMP388, MS5611)
  Baro is now computed from the ICAO standard atmosphere model
  using the filtered altitude — no separate sensor needed unless
  you want to fuse raw pressure for altitude correction.

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 HOW TO RUN
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. Open project in VS Code with PlatformIO installed
2. platformio.ini:
     [env:teensy41]
     platform = teensy
     board = teensy41
     framework = arduino
3. In main.cpp:
     - Create AHRSFilter filter;
     - Call filter.update(accel, gyro, mag, 0.002f) in a 500 Hz ISR or timer
     - Call filter.feedGPS(lla, velNED) in your GPS parse callback
     - Call filter.printCSV() to stream data over USB Serial
4. Read Serial output in MATLAB or Python visualization

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 FILTER ARCHITECTURE  (AHRSFilter.h / .cpp)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Two decoupled stages:

  [1] Madgwick AHRS (attitude)
      - Runs at 500 Hz with every IMU + mag sample
      - Integrates gyro to propagate quaternion
      - Gradient descent on accelerometer corrects tilt
      - Gradient descent on magnetometer corrects yaw/heading
      - No covariance matrix — very fast, works great on Teensy
      - Tuning: beta (default 0.033) — lower = smoother, slower

  [2] 6-state EKF (position + velocity)
      - State:  [px, py, pz, vx, vy, vz]  (NED frame, meters)
      - Predict (500 Hz):
            p += v·dt + ½·a_NED·dt²
            v += a_NED·dt
          where a_NED = R(q) · a_body + [0, 0, g]
      - GPS correct (~10 Hz):
            Sequential scalar Kalman updates for each of 6 measurements
            (pos North, East, Down, vel North, East, Down)
            No matrix inversion needed

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 OUTPUT VARIABLES
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

pos[3]         NED position [m]        from EKF state
vel[3]         NED velocity [m/s]      from EKF state
orient[4]      quaternion [w,x,y,z]    from Madgwick

euler[3]       ZYX Euler [rad]         from quaternion
               [0] = yaw   (heading)
               [1] = pitch
               [2] = roll

heading        yaw in degrees          euler[0] × (180/π), wrapped 0–360
rollPitch[2]   [pitch_deg, roll_deg]   euler[1,2] × (180/π)

altitude       altitude [ft]           = -pos[2] × 3.28084
               (NED Down is negative altitude, × ft/m)

climbRate      climb rate [ft/min]     = -vel[2] × 196.85
               (NED Down velocity, negative = climbing)

airspeed       airspeed [knots]        = √(vx²+vy²+vz²) × 1.944
               (|vel| in m/s → knots)

baroPressure   pressure [Pa]           ICAO 1976 Standard Atmosphere
               Troposphere  (0–11 km): P = 101325 × (1 − 2.256×10⁻⁵h)^5.256
               Tropopause (11–20 km):  P = 22632  × exp(−1.577×10⁻⁴·(h−11000))
               Stratosphere (20–32 km): P = 5475  × (1 + 4.616×10⁻⁶·(h−20000))^−34.16

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 SERIAL OUTPUT (CSV, 20 columns, 500 Hz)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

px, py, pz, vx, vy, vz,
qw, qx, qy, qz,
altitude_ft, climbrate_ftmin, airspeed_kts, heading_deg,
pitch_deg, roll_deg,
yaw_rad, pitch_rad, roll_rad,
baro_pa

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 SIMULATION (MATLAB — trajectory.m / visualize.m)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

RUN TRAJECTORY → generates ground truth + noisy sensor signals
RUN SIMULINK   → runs arcsensors.slx using workspace signals
RUN VISUALIZE  → plots HUD: 3D trajectory, vel, accel, orientation,
                 ground track, and live readout panel

The C++ filter replaces the Simulink insfilterAsync block for
hardware deployment. The math is identical — only the interface
changes from MATLAB workspace variables to live sensor bytes.
